@node Email signatures
@section Email signatures

@vindex org-msg-extras-personal-plain-text-signature
@vindex org-msg-extras-personal-html-signature
@vindex org-msg-extras-work-plain-text-signature
@vindex org-msg-extras-work-html-signature
@samp{org-msg-extras.el} provides four user options for defining email signatures, covering two contexts (personal and work) and two formats (plain text and HTML/Org).

The user option @code{org-msg-extras-personal-plain-text-signature} holds the signature for personal emails sent in plain text format. Its default value is @samp{"\n--\nPablo\n"}, a minimal signature preceded by the conventional @samp{--} separator. The type is a string.

The user option @code{org-msg-extras-personal-html-signature} holds the signature for personal emails composed in Org mode (which @samp{org-msg} exports to HTML). Its default value is @samp{"\n#+begin_signature\n--\n*Pablo*\n#+end_signature"}, using the Org signature block syntax that @samp{org-msg} recognizes. The type is a string.

The user option @code{org-msg-extras-work-plain-text-signature} holds the signature for work emails in plain text. By default it is set to the same value as @code{org-msg-extras-personal-plain-text-signature}, so you only need to customize it if your work signature differs from your personal one. The type is a string.

The user option @code{org-msg-extras-work-html-signature} holds the signature for work emails in Org/HTML format. By default it is set to the same value as @code{org-msg-extras-personal-html-signature}. The type is a string.

These variables are not automatically inserted into messages by @samp{org-msg-extras.el} itself. You should configure your mail user agent or @samp{org-msg} setup to reference the appropriate variable based on the sending account. For example, you might set @code{org-msg-signature} dynamically in a hook based on which email account is active.

